In this project, we are asked to implement a generic multilayer perceptron model. To deal with the convergence issues, some adaptive learning approaches are utilized. Basically, step length and momentum coefficient are two parameters used to solve convergence issues. At each epoch, training samples are shuffled to avoid convergence to local minimum. In the code, an additional neuron is added for threshold in the output layer.

1) Question 1 (XOR Function)

1.a Number of Layers=3

A 3 layered network is constructed. Number of neurons in hidden layer is 9, step length is selected as 2, momentum coefficient is 0.2. Step length is adjusted according to the evolution of total error from epoch to epoch. Finally, learning stops when the total training error becomes less than 0.001

real output for each sample = [ 0, 1, 0, 1 ]

predictions for each sample = [ 0.01808, 0.98498, 0.01478, 0.98502 ]

1.b Number of Layers=4

A 4 layered network is constructed. Number of neurons in each hidden layer is 9, step length is selected as 2, momentum coefficient is 0.2. Step length is adjusted according to the evolution of total error from epoch to epoch. Finally, learning stops when the total training error becomes less than 0.001

real output for each sample = [ 0, 0, 1, 1 ]

predictions for each sample = [ 0.00224, 0.01613, 0.9805, 0.98162 ]

2) Question 2 (Sin(x) Function)

First of all, 60 data points ~U[0,1] are produced. Then, these data points are multiplied by 2*\(\pi\). Y value for each data point is calculated via Sin(x) function. Since Sin(x) function can take values between -1 and 1, unlike the other two questions, hyperbolic tangent function is utilized as an activation function in this question.

2.a Number of Layers=3

A 3 layered network is constructed. Number of neurons in hidden layer is 9, step length is selected as 0.83, momentum coefficient is 0.2. Step length is adjusted according to the evolution of total error from epoch to epoch. Finally, learning stops when the total training error becomes less than 1.1. From the graph below, you can observe the improvement of cost function.

Test with 25 new samples

Finally, additional 25 points are generated from U[0,1]. Through using the trained model, y values of these newly generated points are predicted. From the plot below, you can see the real and predicted value of each data point.

From the plot above, we can see small deviations from real values. During the learning phase, improvement of cost function after a point slows down, and it starts cycling around some points. Therefore, it can not learn the function accurate??y, which can be a reason for these deviations.

2.b Number of Layers=4

A 4 layered network is constructed. Number of neurons in each hidden layer is 10, step length is selected as 1.2, momentum coefficient is 0.2. Step length is adjusted according to the evolution of total error from epoch to epoch. Finally, learning stops when the total training error becomes less than 0.15. From the graph below, you can observe the improvement of cost function.

Test with 25 new samples

Finally, additional 25 points are generated from U[0,1]. Through using the trained model, y values of these newly generated points are predicted. From the plot below, you can see the real and predicted value of each data point.

When a 4 layered structure is formed, cost function continues to decrease rapidly. Therefore, Sin(x) function is learned by the ANN model properly. As a result of this, in this case, deviations between the predicted values and real values are smaller.

3) Question 3 (Iris Data Set)

Iris Data set contains 150 samples. 125 of them are chosen as training samples randomly, and remaining ones are used as test samples. ANN model is used to predict the class of each sample. At each layer of the model, sigmoid function is utilized as an activation function. In this model, there are 3 output layers.

3.a Number of Layers=3

A 3 layered network is constructed. Number of neurons in hidden layer is 10, step length is selected as 1, momentum coefficient is 0.2. Step length is adjusted according to the evolution of total error from epoch to epoch. Finally, learning stops when the total training error becomes less than 3.

Test of remaining points

25 data points above are classified through trained ANN model. We have 3 outputs for each sample, to be able to treat these outputs as probability we should normalize or transform them. We can conduct this operation using the formula below. \[ p_i=\frac{X_i}{\sum_{i=1}^3 X_i}\] In addition to this, I could have used soft max as activation function in the output layer. This activation function ensures that sum of the outputs in the next layer is 1. However, I used sigmoid function, and transformed the outputs for each sample by using the formula above.

3.b Number of Layers=4

A 4 layered network is constructed. Number of neurons in each hidden layer is 10 and 12 respectively. Step length is selected as 1, momentum coefficient is 0.2. Step length is adjusted according to the evolution of total error from epoch to epoch. Finally, learning stops when the total training error becomes less than 3.

Test of remaining points

Remaining 25 data points are classified through trained ANN model. We have 3 outputs for each sample, to be able to treat these outputs as probability we should normalize or transform them. We can conduct this operation using the formula below. \[ p_i=\frac{X_i}{\sum_{i=1}^3 X_i}\] In addition to this, I could have used soft max as activation function in the output layer. This activation function ensures that sum of the outputs in the next layer is 1. However, I used sigmoid function, and transformed the outputs for each sample by using the formula above.
